		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Oraelin</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> Pick One<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Half-Elf<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Rogue<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  The Big Score<br>Greetings, Traveler. What brings you to this part of Oggorok? The ogres don't appreciate your type in the Little Taste of Grobb Inn, you know. What? How is a humble half-elf like myself here? Traveler, traveler.. you really can't tell, can you? Ha Ha! A great jest this will be! Pull up a stool, wayfarer, and I will tell you a tale the likes of which you've never seen.. Follow me closely, Traveler, if you don't like being surprised (You brought your own sewer water? Good! You'll save money on Ogrish ale...)<br>In the infancy of the world, when the races were first establishing the great cities that stand to this day, there were the gods. Tunare, the Plague-Bringer, Rallos Zek and so on. A rather boring bunch, if I may. Every one of them was so serious, either trying to bring peace to the world or smother it in unimaginable darkness. In other words, the same old thing. You have no idea, Traveler, how boring it is to watch the Final Battle being fought every week or so. Wizards versus Necromancers, Paladins fighting Shadow Knights, Trolls goring halflings (halfling skulls are great Ogre delicacies, you know, remind me to give you the recipe..) Anyway, the world was absolutely no fun, and even the gods were beginning to look for new diversions. I believe it happened one day that Rallos Zek and the Prime Healer were playing "bounce the dwarf" in the pantheon, and inspiration was struck:<br>"I will crush you, foul being! I'll rip out your heart, flay the skin from your bones, and visit unimaginable tortures on you for a thousand thousand years!!"<br>"Really, Zekky, I'm sure your handicap will improve. It does no good to threaten the clubs, each god only gets so many sets",The Prime Healer replied.<br>"I know", Zek replied. "It's a good thing I have you for a special friend. Right?"<br>"No, find a "special" guild if you want "special" guys to hang out with," The Prime Healer said. "Now I am going to move away from you."<br>"Oh, who am I kidding!" Rallos Zek moaned. "The heavenly plane is dead! We need to liven up the place! What can we do?"<br>"Another chili-eating contest?" suggested the Prime Healer.<br>"No, last time we did that, we released that sentient Putrid Cloud into the world. They still can't get the smell out in Grobb."<br>"What, then? I suppose we should check the mortals for any amusing individuals. Perhaps we will come up with an idea."<br>Well now, Traveler, at this point in time the world of Norrath was going to Halas in a handbasket. When the gods had created the world, they had assigned a god for every conceivable profession. Necromancers, Warriors, Magicians, merchants, everyone had someone to make sure they didn't get out of hand. But the gods had made one crucial mistake: they hadn't counted on the existence of thieves. So while warlords were being taught to conquer and  Necromancers were taught to keep the books in a way that they could ravage the countryside for one month at no additional cost, Rogues and Bards were running rampant over the countryside. A Thieves Alliance ruled most of the cities, and without a god to direct and moderate them, the crucial balance of the world was being thrown off. No god could bestow on them an appropriate name, so bards named RoboNixon and rogues called The Arrogant Easy were running amok. Also, Traveler, bards with no quality control singing "The Ballad of UO Excellence" literally drove people mad.<br>I, a humble half-elf rogue of the Tenth Rank, was happily making a living in Qeynos off the total dominance that thieves enjoyed.<br>What, Traveler? You say I'm not any rank? Good! You're listening...<br>Things were going pretty good, me making a living on the purses of hapless merchants and spending the nights in the Unlighted Candle Tavern. One night, I was drinking and counting my take (I'd ripped off a very naive merchant called B. McQuaid) when suddenly a very timid little clerk type came in the tavern. Normally, the other denizens of the tavern, many much more nasty than me, wouldn've jumped him faster than Dwarven Spirits burns through your liver. However, the rougher barflys didn't even glance at him. It seemed they acted like he wasn't really there. As I watched this phenomenon curiously, the man came straight up to me.<br>"Stranger, I'd advise you leave before someone less charitable than me decides to take your purse and give you a one way trip to the rations factory." (Sick again, Traveler?)<br>"Sir,"he said in a whiny, high pitched voice, "I have an invisibility spell active. Only you can see me. I've come to inform you of a business proposition my employers are sponsoring."<br>"Hey,"I said, "If it's about that colored sewage project with the water dealer, I don't do that any more." <br>"Sir," he said, "I have come to give you a chance, along with thousands of rogues, to become the GOD of the rogues. The gods are bored, and want a fun-loving scoundrel to lighten up the pantheon. I want you to come with me to the competition that determines who gets the job."<br>"Barkeep!" I yelled. "I'll take another round of whatever I just drank! It seems to be the best batch ever!"<br>"SILENCE, FOOL!" said the clerk, who seemed to have changed into a 50" Wyrm of UnHoly Fire when I'd turned toward the bar (At this bar, with its liquor, not as uncommon as one might think). "YOU WILL COME WITH ME, OR I WILL TURN YOU OVER TO MY DREAD MASTER!!"<br>"Who is?"<br>"Um..well..I know people!" sputtered the Wyrm. "People who will beat you up good!"<br>"Name two."<br>The Wyrm abruptly changed back into the clerk. "Please come with me! Please, please please?" he whined.<br>I still didn't believe the Rogue God story, but I decided to go along with him, just to stop his whining.<br>"Fine," I sighed, "Let's get this over with."<br>"Great! First we have to get you registered. What do you want to be known as in the tournament?"<br>"How about the BlackShadow warrior?"<br>"Listen, buddy," he groaned, "We already have 30 BlackShadows, 17 NightWings, 22 Dark Lords, 15 Ebon Knights, and one guy named the Pink Rogue of Fluffy Bunnies." He paused briefly. "I'm sort of worried about the Pink Rogue of Fluffy Bunnies.."<br>"Whatever, I don't care! Just sign me up, if only to get you to go away!"<br>"DONE AND DONE!!" He thundered. "THE GAMES WILL COMMENCE--NOW!!"<br>With the final word, Traveler, I was leaving the barstool, intent on retiring to bed, but suddenly there was a terrific noise and light, and than everything went black. <br>When I finally woke up, I was on a desolate, gray plain. In all directions, this plain, flat as a tabletop, showed no signs of life. I cursed myself for my stupidity. By agreeing with the man, I could've put myself in the power of an evil wizard or necromancer, and doomed myself to this lower plane (such I thought it was) for eternity.<br>Then I noticed a note, inscribed in the Common Tongue, at my feet. I scooped it up, and this curious note read:<br>"Rogue, take thee straightaway to the north. After a mile or so walk, you will come to the Pantheonic Arena. Here, you will compete with the other rogues in various games of skill to determine the winner. DO NOT LET ANYTHING ALONG THE WAY DELAY YOU, OR THE GODS OF THE GAME WILL LOOK UPON YOUR CANDIDACY WITH DISFAVOR."<br>For the first time, I began to think the little man's story was true. A true rogue God..immortal, possessing unimaginable wealth and power. On the other hand, I had planned going to rob a leather merchant the next day. <br>"Oh well," I thought, "either way is good."<br>So thinking, I began walking north, half-wondering where the other rogues are. My next sight, Traveler, was one I will never forget. A great Arena appeared, very far off in the distance. It stretched into the gray clouds, its full height rising above even them. The walls shone with gold, with precious gems inlayed in the walls. Emeralds, rubies, sapphires, diamonds were displayed as far as the eye can see, more than a rogue could steal in a hundred years. Seeing this, I began to hurry toward this palace of riches. <br>On the way however, another curious sight abruptly materialized to my side in the gray mist. A bent, grizzled old man was slowly shuffling in the opposite direction from me, carrying what looked to be a backpack of rags, and a pitifully small purse. Intrigued, I sneaked behind the man and prepared to take his purse. Suddenly, a majestic, booming voice entered my head: FOOL! DO NOT DELAY IN COMING TO THE GAMES! EVEN THE LOSERS WILL BE SENT AWAY WITH A KING'S RANSOM IN JEWELS! STEAL FROM THAT MAN AT YOUR PERIL!<br>I considered this, and glanced at the shining arena. So full of riches, why should I steal from this man? However, a good rogue takes what he can get when he can get it. Clubbing the man, I quickly rifled through his purse, finding seven copper pieces. I wasn't afraid of the voice. When has a person with a majestice godlike voice that appears in your head ever been able to harm anyone? Name one time, Traveler.<br>I started to walk toward the Arena again. This time, yet another apparition appeared in front of me. A very dignified old elf, in the garb of a wizard, was walking toward the arena. Hungry for some intellectual conversation (A rogue can be smart, you know) I hurried toward the elf.<br>"Greetings, Traveler!" I said. "Are you in the contest as well?"<br>"Hardly", sniffed the elf in a cultured voice. "I was appointed by the Gods as the judge of the ruffians. I will determine the identity of the new god. The gods could not have picked a smarter and more handsome judge. Don't you agree?"<br>If I'd been listening, I probably would have tried to butter him up for the contest. However, my attention had been drawn to the handsome wand at his side. It was made of silver and inlaid with rubies, and it was obviously magical. <br>I thought,"I could get a gold piece for that in Qeynos." Before I thought of any other ramifications, I reached out, struck the elf, and stole his wand. As I was running away, the elf cried: "You fool? You'll never get the job now!" You threw it away for a common wand!"<br>That last thought worried me a little, but I figured he was kidding. Someone told me once wizards like being knocked down and having their wand stolen, and every one before now had liked it (At least I think they did when they regained consciousness on the slave ship).<br>After this, no more interruptions presented themselves. I walked straight up to the Arena door, marveling at the new multitude of riches now apparent at the short distance. I knocked on the door. Behind it, I heard a thump and some muffled cursing, and the door opened, revealing a wizened little gnome dressed in black.<br>"What be ye wantin?", growled the gnome. "I don't have time to answer th' door for every fool driftin' in!"<br>"I'm here for the rogue contest," I replied. "My name is Oraelin."<br>Astonishingly, the gnome burst out laughing. "Oraelin? ORAELIN? The man who stole from a beggar on the way here? The man who knocked out the judge for a silver wand? You want in?? The gods will roast you for disobeying their instructions! You could've had riches even losing if you'd held your greed in check, but now the gods will cast you down to the lower planes with nothing!"<br>"Correction," I said. "With seven copper pieces and a silver wand."<br>The gnome stared at me, and said, "Then come on in, but don't say I didn't warn you."<br>Upon entering the stadium, I was in a small, dirty room with a foul-smelling troll. This troll looked at me, and said, "Duh, you first here. Others have to come wait here now."<br>Time passed (very slowly, as anyone knows who spends time with a troll.) The troll became more and more impatient, finally bursting out: "Go in stadium! Let god deal! Others not here!")<br>I did as he bade, and received the greatest shock I'd ever received in my life. Standing directly in the middle of the Arena was the entire pantheon. Good and evil, all gods were there.<br>As I stood dumbstruck, the voice cried out: ORAELIN! YOU ARE THE ONLY PERSON TO COME ON TIME! MUCH AS WE HATE TO DO IT, YOU MUST BE THE NEW GOD! YOU WILL HAVE POWER AND RICHES BEYOND YOUR MORTAL DREAMS! JOIN US NOW IN THE HEAVENLY PLANE!! SAY THE WORD AND YOU ARE THE KING OF THIEVES!"<br>I'd done it. Despite my mistakes, I'd got it by pure dumb luck. All I had to do was accept, and I'd never have to steal again. But now that I was on the threshold of immortality, I hesitated. Never steal again? Where was the fun it that? Where was the fun of sitting on a cloud, never to outwit merchants, never to travel and adventure again? I then said the hardest thing I'd ever have to say in my life:<br>"No thanks, gods. Life is too much fun, I couldn't stand your existence. Rallos Zek is eying me, too, and I've heard disturbing rumors. Goodbye."<br>A tremendous cheer arose from the pantheon as I said these painful words.<br>"ALL HAIL THE KING OF THE THIEVES! ALL HAIL! ALL HAIL!"<br>"But I.."<br>"YOU WERE THE ONLY ONE TO PASS!" They cried. "YOU ALONE COULDN'T RESIST YOUR SHORT-TERM GREED, YOU ALONE TURNED DOWN THE GODHOOD WHEN IT WAS OFFERED TO YOU! YOU ALONE HAVE THE RIGHT COMBINATION OF PETTY GREED AND STUPIDITY TO BE ONE OF US!"<br>"Well," I said, "when you put it that way, how can I refuse?"<br>The rest, Traveler, is history. What? You don't believe me? I was the last god (except for the Pink Rogue of Fluffy Bunnies, but that's another story.) I'm surprised at you, Traveler. You don't listen very well. I am the King of Thieves and the Lord of Mischief, and I like to come down to Norrath for some fun occasionally. What fun? You are the fun, Traveler. That rather large ogre behind you is your new employer, or master rather. And I will take that purse, thank you. What, Traveler? Oh, he'll set you free is twenty or so years I expect. You should have paid attention, and I AM fond of a joke...<br>One more, Ogg.. they just don't get it, do they, my good Ogre? Ah, well..they never remember, Ogg, who Bristlebane was, and Oraelin always gets them.<br>I must go.. the PlagueBringer and the Tribunal are gearing for war, and I'm supposed to observe.<br>Don't worry, barkeep, I and mine will always survive. After all, isn't there always the day after the Last Battle?<p><p>
<p><p>
		
